She turned to a blank page and noted the date on it. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you reading old memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? It's just a few days away now."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "an error" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in a family otherwise composed solely of boys.
Ivory was non-binary too, in her own way. When she mentioned it, the world seemed to change around her. Tasks were assigned to her that condemned her to solitude as punishment for her difference.
She also had to remain in service to the princess, but that wasn't too bad, as it made her a friend.
"It's soon going to be your birthday, I think?" Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming up in just a few days. Kari nodded, a sad glint in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As iel asked, they remembered what Kari had answered the last time.
"No, Kari replied softly. Ivory knew it was a difficult topic for her. It was the day she was confined to her room and her mother was banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the outrage among the servants and the villagers. iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but she also had this strange ability to predict the future."
"Well... What do you feel like doing?" iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when iel glanced at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" Ivory asked, turning towards the silent princess who was tapping frenetically, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly, seeing the usually reserved princess become passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something not related to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" Ivory suggested as she stood up and made her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and immersed herself in her memories, wrapping herself again in her thick comforter.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things outside her usual range, like paint.
Iel turned back down the corridors, trying not to listen to the murmurings of the maids.
"I've heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, which is why she always goes to that room."
"I've heard she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, don't you think?"
Iel covered his ears, as ignoring them wasn't working. Iel headed towards the royal painter's studio, located in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately worked as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, which according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint spots everywhere, pencils and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every last inch of the wall. Surprisingly, he saw none of that. The room was clean, with a red velvet backdrop and a stool right in front. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, having his portrait painted.
"Ah hello, Ivory! You're coming to watch your future king pose for a portrait, aren't you?" asked Aquilo to Ivory, winking at her.
"Pardon, little prince," replied Iel, partially ignoring him as he searched for the objects his silent friend desired. "I'm here just to get some supplies."
"Ah, the girl is going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box iel had scavenged. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought about it, though. "Oh my dear, you know well that it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!"
"I have to go," said Iel, suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words, which reminded him of all the harm people had said about his gender identity. I want to really distance myself from him.
"Are you leaving us already?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the complaints of the royal painter.
"Ce is not the behavior of a future king!" he rebuked her.
"No one will know. Others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he values his life." He turned towards the painter for a second, then leaned towards Ivory. "What do you think of a romantic rendezvous?" Iel shuddered. Indeed, Iel had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone the heir to the throne.
"Do you not know what the word no means?" he said, pushing the prince out of his way.
"Hell no," replied Prince Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why want a romantic rendezvous with me instead of others? You must have a hundred suitors."
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He threw back his hair, which flew through the cold air.
"Then why me instead of another? I am the palace's threat." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Prince Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
